## 3. Struct layouts (must be byte-exact, x86-64 layout)

The guest musl expects these exact layouts. Get a field wrong and CPython crashes in obscure ways. Verify against `<asm-generic/stat.h>` etc.

**`struct timespec`** (16 bytes): `i64 tv_sec; i64 tv_nsec;`

**`struct iovec`** (16 bytes): `u32/u64 iov_base; u64 iov_len;` — pointer is 32-bit in-guest but the slot is pointer-width; on wasm32 the base is a 4-byte offset. **Define the guest as wasm32 → iovec is 8 bytes: `u32 base; u32 len`.** (This is the one place the wasm32 ABI diverges from x86-64; keep iovec/pointer-bearing structs at wasm32 widths, keep scalar structs like `stat` at their kernel widths.)

**`struct stat`** — use the wasm32/`stat64` shape your musl port declares; the safest move is to **let the guest musl define it and have the host fill fields by name via a shared header**, rather than hardcoding offsets. At minimum populate: `st_dev, st_ino, st_mode, st_nlink, st_uid, st_gid, st_rdev, st_size, st_blksize, st_blocks, st_atim, st_mtim, st_ctim`.

**`struct sockaddr_in`** (16 bytes): `u16 sin_family; u16 sin_port(BE); u32 sin_addr(BE); u8 pad[8]`.
**`struct sockaddr_in6`** (28 bytes): `u16 family; u16 port(BE); u32 flowinfo; u8 addr[16]; u32 scope_id`.

**`struct epoll_event`** (packed, **12 bytes on x86-64**, `__attribute__((packed))`): `u32 events; u64 data`. Keep it packed — this bites people.

**`struct pollfd`** (8 bytes): `i32 fd; i16 events; i16 revents`.

**`struct linux_dirent64`** (variable): `u64 d_ino; i64 d_off; u16 d_reclen; u8 d_type; char d_name[]` (NUL-terminated, whole record padded to 8). Used by `getdents64` — importlib scans package dirs with this, so it must be correct or imports fail.

