## 9. Permanently-ENOSYS list (fail loud, document it)

`execve`, `ptrace`, `mount`, `reboot`, `init_module`, `bpf`, `io_uring_*` (v1), `userfaultfd`, `perf_event_open`, `keyctl`, raw `clone` with unsupported flags. Returning a *clean* `-ENOSYS` (not a crash) for these is a feature: it turns "mysterious runtime hang" into "build-time / import-time error we can show the user." Your build farm should surface these as "package X needs syscall Y — unsupported."

---

## 10. The one paragraph to keep in mind

None of this makes Wasm faster or denser — Wasm was already dense. This layer decides *which software is allowed through the door*. Every syscall you implement unlocks packages across **every** language at once (that's the O(1) win over per-package porting). Build P0/P1 backed by `wasmtime-wasi`, get a FastAPI app answering HTTP, add the pre-init snapshot for the 1 ms cold-start demo — that sequence is a shippable product before you ever touch threads or fork.

